  "enhanced_information": "Sertoli cells, located within the seminiferous tubules of the testes, play a crucial role in supporting and nourishing developing sperm cells through the process of spermatogenesis. One of the key functions of Sertoli cells is the secretion of androgen-binding protein (ABP), which is stimulated by follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). ABP helps to maintain high concentrations of testosterone in the vicinity of the developing sperm by binding testosterone, which is primarily produced by the Leydig cells adjacent to the seminiferous tubules. This local increase in testosterone concentration is critical for the proper development of sperm. Luteinizing hormone (LH), although vital for stimulating testosterone production in Leydig cells, is not secreted by Sertoli cells but by the pituitary gland. The evidence paths confirm the interaction of androgen-binding proteins with germ cells and testosterone, supporting the role of Sertoli cells in concentrating testosterone through ABP. Additionally, the paths clarify that testosterone is indeed produced by Leydig cells, not Sertoli cells, aligning with the corrected reasoning chains."
